<h1>To Robert Stewart</h1>

<div class="docbody">
<div class="opener">
<table class="salutationBlock">
        <tr>
		<td class="salutationLeft">To Captain Robert Stewart, at Maidstone.<br/> Sir,</td>
		<td class="salutationRight">[Winchester, 22 July 1756]</td>
	      </tr>
      </table>
</div>
<p>Herewith I enclose you two plans of the kind of Forts that are intended to be builtone of the ground-work, the other of the Houses and all conveniences; with such directions, that I think it impossible for you to errif you will attend thereto.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-03-02-0258-fn-0001" id="GEWN-02-03-02-0258-fn-0001-ptr">1</a> Enclosed you will also receive a list of such Tools as I have been able to procure; with which, and such as you may get of the Inhabitants, by borrowing, hiring and buying, you must be content.<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-03-02-0258-fn-0002" id="GEWN-02-03-02-0258-fn-0002-ptr">2</a> These must be put into the hands of the best tradesmen, and most laborious workmen; who will receive six-pence extraordinary pay, for every day they work: an account whereof must be kept (exactly) by yourself and officers. The men that remain after the Workers are draughted, must act as covering parties to prevent surprizes; against which you must carefully guard. It is impossible for me to fix upon the identical piece of
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-02-03-02-pb-0283">[283]</span>
ground to erect this fort ontherefore I shall confine you to the most convenient spot, between the mouth of Sleepy-Creek and Barracks, which you will make choice of, with the approbation of your officers. There is a Hill which overlooks Boyles field, and extensive country round that may be made infinitely strong, and will answer the purpose well<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-03-02-0258-fn-0003" id="GEWN-02-03-02-0258-fn-0003-ptr">3</a>If it is not <span class="hi-italic" style="font-style: italic;">too</span> high and inaccessable; this you must examine into.</p>
<p>I have too great an opinion of your good sense and discretion to think you need any admonition to induce you to a diligent discharge of your Duty! You see our situation, know our danger, and bear witness of the peoples sufferings: which are sufficient excitements to a generous mind.</p>
<p>As many things will occur that I can not possibly direct inlet the interest of the Service and your own prudenceassisted by the advice of the Officers under your command, be your direction. This instant I received yours of yesterdays date,<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-03-02-0258-fn-0004" id="GEWN-02-03-02-0258-fn-0004-ptr">4</a> and am extremely sorry that the Indians have visited us at this critical juncture of Harvestingespecially as it will prevent your proceedings in the operations orderedas your conduct must be guided by the movements and numbers of the Enemy, I will not take upon me to order positively at this distance; but recommend it to you to consult your Officers on all occasions, and act by their advice. If you can learn from good intelligence, that their numbers are great and motions designed for Virginiaendeavour to give the inhabitants notice that they may lodge their women and children, and assist against the enemy.</p>
<p>If you find they are only flying parties of the IndiansI would advise the Settlers by no means to neglect their harvest, as their whole support depends upon it, and your assistance to get it in.</p>
<p>I must order, above all things, that you will send out small parties, or rather single persons as spies every day, up and down the river for a number of miles, to see if they can make any discovery of the enemys crossing. I have sent you two barrels of powder, and four Boxes of Ball: as to cartridge-paper, I neither have nor can get any upon no terms.</p>
<p>You must get Horns and Pouches,<a class="ptr" href="#GEWN-02-03-02-0258-fn-0005" id="GEWN-02-03-02-0258-fn-0005-ptr">5</a> if you send over the neighbourhood for them.</p>
<p>Transmit me constant accounts of the enemy, if they continue in your neighbourhood. I am &amp;c.</p>
<div class="closer">
<p class="signed">G:W.</p>
<span class="pb" title="page number in print edition (no page scan available)" id="GEWN-02-03-02-pb-0284">[284]</span>
<div class="dateline-closer">Winchester, July 22, 1756.</div>
</div>
</div>
<div class="docback">
<div class="note-source" id="GEWN-02-03-02-0258-sn">

   <p>
<abbr title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ Letter Book Copy: letters copied into a bound letter-book ]">LB</abbr>, <span class="ref-rep" title="fade=[ on ] fadespeed=[0.1] windowlock=[on] cssbody=[ boxover ] header=[]  body=[ U.S. Library of Congress, George Washington Papers, Washington, D.C. ]">DLC:GW</span>.
</p>

</div>
<div id="fn" class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-03-02-0258-fn-0001-ptr" id="GEWN-02-03-02-0258-fn-0001">1</a>

   <p>For a discussion of GWs plans for the frontier forts, see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-03-02-0255&amp;expandNote=GEWN-02-03-02-0255-fn-0001#GEWN-02-03-02-0255-fn-0001" class="document">GW to Thomas Waggener, 21 July 1756, n.1</a>. Presumably the plans GW sent to Robert Stewart were similar or identical to those that he sent to Waggener and to Peter Hog on 21 July.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-03-02-0258-fn-0002-ptr" id="GEWN-02-03-02-0258-fn-0002">2</a>

   <p>GWs enclosed list has not been found, but see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-03-02-0257" class="document">GWs Orders of this date</a> for the list of tools and ammunition that he ordered to be sent to Conococheague (Maidstone).</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-03-02-0258-fn-0003-ptr" id="GEWN-02-03-02-0258-fn-0003">3</a>

   <p>Barracks was probably Berwicks, or Barwicks (see <a href="default.xqy?keys=GEWN-print-02-03-02-0263" class="document">Robert Stewart to GW, 23 July 1756</a>). Thomas Berwick (Barwick) of Frederick County had a cabin and milldam on Warm Spring Run near the Potomac River. James Boyle (died c.1758) owned two separate tracts of land near the Warm Springs. Warm Spring Run flows into the Potomac above, or to the west of, Sleepy Creek. Berwick, whose place GW visited in 1748 while surveying Lord Fairfaxs lands on the South Branch, was an officer in the Frederick County militia in the 1750s.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-03-02-0258-fn-0004-ptr" id="GEWN-02-03-02-0258-fn-0004">4</a>

   <p>Stewarts letter of 21 July 1756 has not been found.</p>

</div>
<div class="footnote"><a class="note-ref" href="#GEWN-02-03-02-0258-fn-0005-ptr" id="GEWN-02-03-02-0258-fn-0005">5</a>

   <p>GW means powder horns and bullet pouches.</p>

</div>
</div>
